	<h2>An introduction</h2>

	I have more than <span class="phish-highlight">700 Phish shows</span> on my external hard drive. At about three hours a show, that means I have 2100 hours of Phish in my collection, which equates to about 87 days. That’s not atypical, as far as Phish collections go. <br /><br />

	Phish is my favorite band. But unfortunately, Phish is surprisingly inaccessible to casual music listeners. <i>Think about what you do when a friend recommends some new music to you</i>. Most people go on YouTube, maybe choose the first song in the search results, and form their opinions on the artist within the first 30 seconds of the song.<br /><br />

	Will doing this hook you on Phish?<br /><br />

	Maybe, maybe not. <br /><br />

	Phish is a <span class="phish-highlight">jam band</span>. A great amount of a jam band’s appeal is the <span class="phish-highlight">improvisational, extended jams</span> in and around their songs. These jams can vary significantly from performance to performance, and add a sense of <span class="phish-highlight">variety, energy, personality, and freshness</span> to what would otherwise just be another song on record.<br /><br />

	This sense of variation can do wonders. Just how different are different versions of a song? Let’s take a look at the numbers; the below chart shows the lengths of every version of the song <i>Tweezer</i> played in the last two years:<br /><br />

	(insert chart here)<br /><br />

	What exactly does this variation mean? Well, it means that if this music resonates with you, then it will <span class="phish-highlight">really</span> resonate with you.<br /><br />

	<i>It’s like having a plate of food in front of you at dinner; one item on the plate is your favorite food in the world, and the rest just pales in comparison to it, at least in your mind. Maybe you save this item on your plate for last, or maybe you eat it first for immediate gratification. You want more, but there isn’t any.<br /><br />

	Now, imagine if this item of food was available to you at almost <span class="phish-highlight">infinite quantities</span> at the dinner table. Better yet, imagine if each successive bite of this item tasted a little bit better and lasted a little bit longer than the bite before it.</i><br /><br />

	<b>That is the anatomy of Phish jams</b>. Most versions of the same song are <span class="phish-highlight">sufficiently distinctive</span> such that you’ll want to listen to all of them. Phish also records each of their shows professionally and releases each of them to the public for download. <br /><br />

	Well, what exactly does that mean?<br /><br />

	That means that in contrast to your favorite artist who releases an album once every year or two, Phish is <span class="phish-highlight">constantly and consistently creating new music</span>. After every show, there is something new that I want to download and listen to. After every show, my favorite band has effectively released new music. <br /><br />

	That is why Phish is so exciting.<br /><br />

